Priority 4: Strengthen Indigenous Section

Replace the existing Indigenous tab with this more grounded version:

```html
<div id="indigenous" class="tab-pane">
    <h2><i class="fas fa-hands-helping"></i> Indigenous land management · Observation-based learning</h2>
    <p>Acknowledging Tasmanian Aboriginal (<em>palawa/pakana</em>) land management practices and their relevance to modern weed management in lutruwita/Tasmania.</p>

    <div class="info-card">
        <i class="fas fa-fire"></i>
        <h4>Cultural burning vs uniform disturbance</h4>
        <p>Western fire management often treats whole blocks uniformly. Tasmanian Aboriginal mosaic burning creates patchworks of different ages and burn intensities.</p>
        <div class="field-signal"><strong>Key insight:</strong> Patchy heat creates refuges for native insects and plants, breaks weed seedbank continuity, reduces massive post-fire germination.</div>
        <p><strong>Application:</strong> Consider patch-burn strategies. Consult with Tasmanian Aboriginal land management organisations before designing fire-based weed programs. Traditional knowledge is not a free resource — engagement requires relationship, respect, and reciprocity.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="info-card">
        <i class="fas fa-calendar-alt"></i>
        <h4>Reading the land, not the calendar</h4>
        <p>Instead of fixed dates ("spray in October"), read seasonal indicators: flowering events, insect activity, soil moisture. Tasmanian seasons are variable — adapt to conditions, not dates.</p>
        <div class="field-signal"><strong>Example:</strong> Use wattle flowering as your trigger for spring control, not a calendar date. Phenology adapts to actual conditions.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-card">
        <i class="fas fa-tree"></i>
        <h4>Decision-making without written rules</h4>
        <p>Tasmanian Aboriginal land management traditionally operates without written manuals — knowledge is transmitted through observation, oral tradition, and multi-generational feedback loops.</p>
        <div class="field-signal"><strong>Application to you:</strong> Your field notes, mistakes, and observations become tomorrow's tacit knowledge. Start a Tasmanian weed field journal today. Write down what you see, what worked, what failed.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="disclaimer">
        <i class="fas fa-hands"></i> <strong>Acknowledgement:</strong> We recognise Tasmanian Aboriginal people as the original land managers of lutruwita/Tasmania. This section is meant to prompt reflection, not represent traditional knowledge. For deeper learning, engage directly with Tasmanian Aboriginal organisations and Traditional Owners.
    </div>
</div>
